Introduction to Probability

  • Probability Theory is a theoretical way to quantify laws of chance
  • Based on a set of assumptions, axioms, and principles
  • Probability is the “language” of Statistics
    • Statistics more than charts, means, stddev, and percentiles
    • Statistical Analysis is used extensively for inference
      • Statistical significance
      • Prediction –via linear regression
      • Quantify margin of errors, p-values, etc. without resorting to Bootstrapping?

Introduction to Probability –Basic Definitions

  • need to calculate the probability of an eventA, P(A)
  • Sample Space –contains elementary outcomes
    • Toss a coin once, twice, thrice. S = {H,T}, S={HH, HT, TH, TT}
    • Roll a die, S = {1,2,3,4,5,6). Roll a die twice, S = {(1,1),….,(6,6)}
  • Each individual element of the sample space S is an elementary outcome
  • Event A occurs when one or more of the corresponding elementary events occur
  • general, any event A is a subset of the sample space

Introduction to Probability –Basic Definitions

  • Finite, Countable, and Uncountable Sample Spaces
  • A) needs to satisfy some basic properties
    • = P(A) <= 1, for all A
    • = Sum of the probabilities of the elementary events comprising A
    • U B) = P(A) + P(B) if A and B are disjoint
    • = 1
  • A) is really the proportion of times A will occur if the experiment is repeated a large number of times
  • calculate probability of an event A, we need to calculate / assign the probability of the elementary events in the sample space

Relationship Between Odds and Probability

  • the odds of an event A occurs is 3 to 1, what is P(A)?
    • = 3/(3+1) = 0.75
  • the odds of an event A occurs is 2 to 3, what is P(A)?
    • = 2 / (2+3) = 2/5 = 0.4
  • P(A) = 0.8, what are the odds that A will occur
    • Odds are 4 to 1
    • Could the odds be 8 to 2?
    • Odds for A = P(A) / (1 -P(A))

Example: Actual Odds Versus Payoff Odds

  1. Find the actual odds against the outcome of 13.
  2. How much net profit would you make if you win by betting $5 on 13?
  3. the casino was not operating for profit and the payoff odds were changed to match the actual odds against 13, how much would you win if the outcome were 13?

If you bet $5 on the number 13 in roulette, your probability of winning is 1/38, but the payoff odds are given by the casino as 35:1.

Example: Actual Odds Versus Payoff Odds

a. With and , we get

Actual odds against 13

b. Net Profit

Casino payoff odds against 13 are 35:1. For a $5 bet, the net profit is $175.

The winning bettor would collect $175 plus the original $5 bet.

After winning, the total amount collected would be $180, for a net profit of $175.

  1. Net Profit if payoff odds matched actual odds
  2. the casino were not operating for profit, the payoff odds would be changed to 37:1,

For a $5 bet, the net profit would be $185.

(The casino makes its profit by providing a profit of only $175 instead of the $185 that would be paid with a roulette game that is fair instead of favoring the casino.)

Examples with Unions and Intersections and Complements

  • = {overweight}, B = {Male}
  • A) = 0.36, P(B) = 0.5, P(AB) = 0.18
  • Calculate P(AB), P(A U B), P(ABc), P(AcB), P(AcBc) and P(Ac U Bc)
  • AB) = 0.18
    • f overweight people are males
  • A U B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(AB) = 0.36 + 0.5 - 0.18 = 0.68
  • ABc) = P(A) - P(AB) = 0.36 - 0.18 = 0.18
    • f overweight people are females
  • AcB) = P(B) - P(AB) = 0.5 - 0.18 = 0.32
    • f not overweight people are males
  • AcBc) = P(Ac) - P(AcB) = 1 - 0.36 - 0.32 = 0.32
    • f people are female and not overweight
    • Note that P(AcBc) = 1 - P(A U B)
  • Ac U Bc) = P(Ac) + P(Bc) - P(AcBc) = 0.64 + 0.5 - 0.32 = 0.82
    • Note that P(Ac U Bc) = 1 - P(AB)

Independence

Conditional Probability Summary

  • an event B has occurred, it may change our assessment of another event A
  • A | B ) is the “revised” estimate of probability of A happening
  • (A | B) = P(AB) / P(B)
    • relative freq of A relative to B
  • A) is the unconditional probability of A
  • A | B) is the conditional probability of A given B

Independent Events

  • Events A and B are independent if occurrence of B does not affect the probability of A
  • P(A|B) = P(A)
  • This also means that P(AB) = P(A)P(B)
  • show two events are independent, it is enough to show that the probability of their intersection is the product of the two probabilities

Independent Events - Example 1

  • Box has 60 Red items and 40 Blue items. I pick 2 items at random w/o replacing.
  • R1 and R2 are events {Red item in first draw} and {Red item in second draw}
  • Are the two events independent?
  • Note that
    • R1) = 0.6
  • R2 | R1) = 59/99 = P( R1 R2) / P(R1)
  • R1 * R2) = P(R2 | R1) * P(R1) = 0.6 * 59/99
  • show independence, have to show that
    • R1 R2 ) = P(R1) * P(R2)
  • What is the P(R2) = P(R2 | R1) * P(R1) + P(R2 | B1) * P(B1)

= 59/99 * 0.6 + 60/99 * 0.4 = 0.6

  • R1 R2) = 0.6*59/99 =? 0.6 * 0.6
  • Hence R1 and R2 are not independent

Independent Events - Example 2

  • Does the previous example change if we replace the items after the first draw?
  • Box has 60 Red items and 40 Blue items. I pick 2 items at random with replacement.
  • R1 and R2 are events {Red item in first draw} and {Red item in second draw}
  • Are the two events independent?
  • R2|R1) remains at 60/100 = P(R2)
  • Hence independent

Extending Independence To More Than Two Events

  • Concept of pairwise and mutual independence
  • Example: Toss 2 coins
    • = { H in first toss} = {HT, HH}
    • = {H in second toss} = {TH, HH}
    • = {Both heads or both tails} = {HH, TT}
  • A) = ½, P(B) = ½. P(C) = 1/2
  • AB) = P(HH) = ¼ = P(A) * P(B)
  • BC) = P(HH) = ¼ = P(B) * P(C)
  • AC) = P(HH) = ¼ = P(A) * P(C)
  • ABC) = P(HH) /= P(A) * P(B) * P(C)
  • Hence A B and C are pairwise independent but NOT mutually independent
  • For mutual independence, all possible combos have to have the property of multiplicativeness

Important Total Probability Formula

  • A) = P(A|B) * P(B) + P(A|Bc) * P(Bc)
  • Useful when occurence of A depends on whether B has occurred or not
  • Carol and Karl are Help Desk resources
  • Carol takes 60% of the calls, Karl - 40%
  • Carol makes 4% errors, Karl makes 6% errors
  • call comes to the help desk. Probability that there will be an error?
  • Need to know who fields the call - Carol and Karl.
  • Don’t know. Hence condition on that event

P(A) = P(A|B) * P(B) + P(A|Bc) * P(Bc)

P(Error) = P(Error / C) P(C) + P(Error / K) * P(K)

= 0.04 * 0.6 + 0.06 * 0.4 = 0.048

Notice the weighted probability calculation

Bayes’ Rule

Bayes’ Rule

  • Drug Company X says its drug is 95% effective in detecting stereoids in athletes who use them. Athlete “Bond” just tested positive. What is the probability that he was using steroids?
  • Setting up the problem
    • Let D be the event that test is positive. Is P(D) = 0.95?
    • Let U be the event that an athlete uses steroids. What is P(D|U)? This is 0.95
    • What are we after? P(U | D) = Probability that the athlete was using steroids given that the test came up positive

Bayes’ Rule

Calculating P(U | D)

    • U | D) = P(UD) / P(D).
    • don’t know P(D) or P(U D).
    • U | D) = P(D | U) * P(U) / P(D)
  • Assume False Positive percentage is 15%, ie 15% of time the drug will “convict” an innocent athlete.
  • Also assume 10% of the athletes use steroids

Bayes’ Rule

    • U) = Probability that an athlete uses steroids = 0.1
    • D|Uc) = Probability that test is positive on a “clean” athlete = 0.15
    • D) = 0.95 * 0.1 + 0.15 * 0.90 = 0.095 + 0.135 = 0.23
      • The Drug tests positive 23% of the time
    • U | D) = 0.95 * 0.1 / 0.23 = 0.095 / 0.23 = 0.41
      • That is, the chance that the athlete is steroid user given that the test is positive is 41%

Combinations Rule (Needed for some probability problems)

A sample of n elements is to be drawn from a set of N elements. Then, the number of different samples possible is denoted by ”N Choose n” or NCn

where the factorial symbol (!) means that

For example,

0! is defined to be 1.

Example - Birthday Problem

  • at least one birthday pair in a group of N people). Same as
    • - P(everyone in a group of N people have different birthdays)
  • everyone in a group of N people have different birthdays) can be calculated as follows
    • Total # of ways in which N people can have birthdays = 365N
    • Total # of ways in which no two people have the same birthday
      • * 364 * . . . . * (365 - N + 1)
  • Hence desired probability is
    • [ 365 * 364 * . . . . * (365 - N + 1) / 365N]
